### Proposal

Currently, Bootstrap sets the `transition` value if transitions are enabled and then sets `transition: none;` in `(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)`:

```scss
@if $enable-transitions {
  @if nth($transition, 1) != null {
    transition: $transition;
  }

  @if $enable-reduced-motion and nth($transition, 1) != null and nth($transition, 1) != none {
    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      transition: none;
    }
  }
}
```

Instead, transitions should be set in `(prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)`.

```scss
@if $enable-transitions {
  @if nth($transition, 1) != null {
    @if $enable-reduced-motion and nth($transition, 1) != none {
      @media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference) {
        transition: $transition;
      }
    } @else {
      transition: $transition;
    }
  }
}
```

### Motivation and context

The `prefers-reduced-motion` media query has [94.76 % global support](https://caniuse.com/?search=prefers-reduced-motion).
If someone uses a browser that does not support this media query, they will see the transitions.
It is preferable that websites are accessible by default, which means that animations should be enabled when the browser indicates `no-preference`.

This is open for debate because perhaps some browsers do not set `prefers-reduced-motion` to `no-preference` by default.

